{"key":"post-12932806","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12932806</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Mad_Hatter2004 said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I wasn't trying to be harsh,but it seems ridiculous to me to make four small holes if they're just for GE,I'd prefer to make one GE hole and that's it.And you place a piece of tape over the puncture in the filter disc when you are done inoculating...or use RTV silicone ontop of the filter disc with a hole in the lid directly underneath...voila,self healing injection port.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This is not a good idea.&amp;nbsp; Filter disks are infinitely re-usable, and if you start poking needles through them, they won't last for ten years or longer like mine have.&amp;nbsp; In addition, smaller gas exchange holes are much better than larger ones.&amp;nbsp; I'd suggest four small holes, not larger than 1/8&quot;.&amp;nbsp; Larger holes tend to cause invitro pinning in the jars, as well as drying of the grains.&amp;nbsp; Smaller holes keep the CO2 level in the jars very high, preventing pinning until you've spawned the grains to your bulk substrate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;By the time one moves up to grains and filter disks, it's assumed he's moved beyond using syringe inoculation.&amp;nbsp; They're fine for the brf tek, but for grains it's preferable to inoculate with an agar wedge.&amp;nbsp; Or, as psuper said, you can lift the lid to inoculate rather than puncture the filter disk.&amp;nbsp; However, moving up to grains opens up a new level of growing, so it's a good time to learn agar and strain isolation.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12933082</next>\n<prev>12932735</prev>\n<first>12931378</first>\n<last>12933367</last>\n<when>1279769331</when>\n<utime>07/22/10 06:28 